[1] Case update
- Thu 6 Sep 2018. Epidemiological situation report, DRC Ministry of Health [in French, machine trans., edited]
https://us13.campaign-archive.com/?u=89e5755d2cca4840b1af93176&id=540896bcd7

The epidemiological situation of the Ebola Virus Disease dated 5 Sep 2018.
A total of 129 cases of haemorrhagic fever were reported in the region, including 98 confirmed and 31 probable.
- 7 suspected cases are under investigation.
- 2 new confirmed cases, including 1 in Beni and 1 in Masereka.
- The confirmed case in Masereka is a health worker who is a known contact of Beni but who refused follow-up and vaccination.
- 2 confirmed cases, including 1 in Beni and 1 in Masereka.

News of the response
Minister of health visits Beni and Butembo
-------------------
-The Minister of health, Dr. Oly Ilunga Kalenga, made a field trip to Beni Thu 6 Sep 2018. Accompanied by the director of the National Institute of Biomedical Research (INRB), professor Jean-Jacques Muyembe, and Dr Njdoloko Tambwe Bathe, the coordinator of the response, participated in Radio Okapi's "Parole aux Auditeurs" interactive show in the Ndindi neighborhood, where they answered questions from the public about Ebola. The delegation then flew to Butembo, where they held a working session with the teams on the spot. They also brought the equipment to install the mobile laboratory in Butembo to speed up the analysis of the samples taken.

Vaccination
----------
- Since the beginning of the vaccination on 8 Aug 2018, 6486 people have been vaccinated, including 3279 in Mabalako, 1930 in Beni, 1067 in Mandima, 121 in Oicha, 70 in Katwa (Butembo), and 19 in Kinshasa.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Mary Marshall

[One can see the continuing steady but slow increase in cases. It would be informative to know what questions the public had during Radio Okapi's "Parole aux Auditeurs" interactive show to get a better idea of their concerns. Holding this forum for the public to address their concerns is an excellent approach to getting them involved in the response. The installation of a mobile laboratory in Butembo to speed up the analysis of the samples taken is also an excellent proactive approach. - Mod LK]

- Wed 5 Sep 2018. Epidemiological situation report, DRC Ministry of Health [in French, machine trans., edited]
https://us13.campaign-archive.com/?u=89e5755d2cca4840b1af93176&id=8f3f23cc5f


The epidemiological situation of the Ebola virus disease dated 4 Sep 2018:
- A total of 127 cases of haemorrhagic fever were reported in the region, of which 96 were confirmed and 31 were probable.
- 4 suspected cases are under investigation.
- 3 new confirmed cases, including 1 in Mabalako, 1 in Mandima, and 1 in Butembo.
- Investigations revealed that a confirmed case in Beni came from Kalunguta, a rural health area between Beni and Butembo. The patient is already cured and has been discharged from the Ebola Treatment Center (ETC).
- 2 deaths of confirmed cases, including 1 in Beni and 1 in Butembo.

News of the response
Coordination in Butembo
--------------
- On Tue 4 Sep 2018, a sample taken from a person who died in Butembo was positive for Ebola. This is the 1st confirmed case of Ebola in Butembo. This is a contact from Beni who refused to cooperate with the health authorities and fled to Butembo after falling ill.

- He died at Butembo University Hospital. The hospital's health staff, having already been trained on how to deal with suspected cases, complied with individual protection measures. The burial has been secured.

- For several days, a coordination monitoring team had already settled in Butembo after receiving information that several contacts living in Beni had moved to Butembo.

- On Wed 5 Sep 2018, response coordinator Dr Ndjoloko Tambwe Bathe traveled to Butembo with other coordinators to set up a full response team. They also identified the location sites of the mobile laboratory and a new CTE (the 5th to date). Vaccination of identified 1st contacts was also able to begin.

Port of entry monitoring
------------
- The National Border Health Program (PNHF) has established a mapping of population mobility in the areas affected by the epidemic in collaboration with the World Organization for Migration (IOM). This mapping has identified 5 priority areas for strengthening surveillance at ports of entry. These 5 priorities are as follows:
- Mangina - Kyanzaba - Mabalako
- Mangina - Beni
- Beni - Maboya - Butembo
- Beni - Bunia / Beni - Kisangani
- Beni - Kasindi

Vaccination
----------
Since vaccination began on 8 Aug 2018, 6343 people have been vaccinated, including 3210 in Mabalako, 1856 in Beni, 1067 in Mandima, 121 in Oicha, 70 in Katwa (Butembo), and 19 in Kinshasa.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Mary Marshall

[See more information on the death in Butembo in the post below, an unfortunate indication that the outbreak continues to spread. But the vaccine and therapeutics appear to be working well, so it is hoped they will be equally effective in stopping further expansion of the disease in Butembo. The difficulty of access to the contacts creates concern.

A question is whether the fatal case was a man or woman. Here the pronoun "he" is used, but in the reports below, it is stated the fatal case is a woman.

It should be noted that there had been 2 earlier cases listed as probable, reported in Butembo, prior to the current cases now being reported. Those earlier cases appear to have been fatal but did not spread to others. - Mod.LK]

- 4 Sep 2018. Ebola WHO external situation report no. 5, WHO Regional office for Africa [edited]
https://tinyurl.com/y8jlb7ds

Situation report
----------
The date [Sat 1 Sep 2018] marks one month since the declaration of the Ebola virus disease (EVD) outbreak in North Kivu and Ituri provinces, Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC). The Ministry of Health, WHO, and partners have made progress in response to the outbreak during this time. Recent trends (Figure 1) suggest that control measures are working; however, these trends must be interpreted with caution.

Since our last situation report on Tue 28 Aug 2018 (external situation report no. 4), an additional 11 new EVD cases (8 confirmed and 3 probable) and 7 new deaths have been reported. Nine other suspected cases are currently under investigation to confirm or exclude EVD. [See updated case numbers in MoH report above.]

Table 1: EVD cases by classification and health zones in North Kivu and Ituri provinces, DRC, as of Sun 2 Sep 2018

Figure 1: Confirmed and probable EVD cases by week of illness onset, data as of Sun 2 Sep 2018 (n=118)*

Figure 2: Confirmed and probable EVD cases by age and sex, North Kivu and Ituri provinces, DRC, Sun 26 Aug 2018 (n=113)

Figure 3: Geographical distribution of confirmed and probable EVD cases in North Kivu and Ituri provinces, DRC, Tue 4 Sep 2018 (n=122)

- Current risk assessment
- Strategic approach to the prevention, detection, and control of EVD

Actions to date
---------
- Coordination of the response
- Surveillance
- Laboratory
- Risk management
- Infection prevention and control (IPC) and water, sanitation, and hygiene (WASH)
- Implementation of ring vaccination protocol
- Psychosocial care
- Risk communication, social mobilization, and community engagement
- Resource mobilization
- Preparedness
- Operations partnership
- IHR travel measures and cross-border health

Conclusions: see report

--
