[This is an excellent comprehensive report on the Ebola outbreak in the DRC with maps and figures showing case numbers and more. - Mod.LK]

******
[2] Butembo ex Beni fatal case and new cases
- Wed 5 Sep 2018. DR Congo records 1st Ebola death in major eastern trade hub. Butembo ex Beni fatal case.
Source: Reuters Report [edited]
https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-ebola-congo/congo-records-first-ebola-death-in-major-eastern-trade-hub-idUSKCN1LL1FG

Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) has recorded its 1st death from Ebola in the eastern trading hub of Butembo, a city of almost a million with links to Uganda that could complicate efforts to control the outbreak, health officials said on [Wed 5 Sep 2018].

The epidemic is believed to have killed 85 people since July and infected another 39. Most have been in villages, but about 20 cases have been in Beni, a city of several hundred thousand people with close links to Uganda.

Butembo, about 55 km [34 miles] away, is 2 or 3 times the size of Beni. It straddles a major trading route for consumer goods entering Congo from East Africa and for Congolese exports of artisanal gold, coltan, timber, and other materials to East African ports via Uganda.

"Ebola case from Beni has died in Butembo DRC," Peter Salama, the World Health Organization's head of emergency operations, wrote on Twitter. "Good news is case detected quickly, response already in place and expanding. Bad new(s) is increases risk of further spread and having Ebola in an urban center makes ending the outbreak much harder," he said.

Butembo's mayor, Sylvain Kanyamanda, said the victim was a woman who was likely infected as a result of participating in an unsafe burial. She died in a university clinic. "We call on the population to exercise caution and to respect all hygiene measures recommended by health workers," he said.

Health officials say they have made progress slowing the virus's spread with experimental vaccines and treatments. But they cannot be sure the situation is under control due to difficulties accessing some areas.

Two South African peacekeepers were wounded in a rebel ambush near the epicenter of an Ebola outbreak in eastern DRC, their UN mission said on [Tue 4 Sep 2018].

[Byline: Fiston Mahamba. Additional reporting by Tom Miles in Geneva; writing by Tim Cocks and Alessandra Prentice]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Mary Marshall

[There is great concern over this death, as it indicates spread of Ebola virus from Beni to Butembo, about 55 km (34 miles) away and a major urban center, as pointed out in a tweet by Peter Salama, the World Health Organization's head of emergency operations. The likelihood that the woman who died was infected during an unsafe funeral again highlights how critical it is to educate the populace on safe funeral practices, especially during Ebola outbreaks.

The healthcare workers (HCWs) in the facility where the patient died will need to be monitored carefully and kept separate from patients, if these HCWs were not vaccinated. Similarly, patients and others who may have had contact with the infected woman also must be monitored and vaccinated. This is complicated by the danger of working in the areas of the country where, because of the violence, contacts are difficult to reach.

In a Huff Post report (https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/world-health-organization-ebola-congo-warning_us_5b9022cfe4b0162f47296009), Salama was reported to have said that "this outbreak is a prototype of the rising number of outbreaks of the future: one that spreads to more populated areas. As HuffPost has previously reported, outbreaks of the worst kinds of pathogens -- ones with the highest mortality rates and limited countermeasures -- are on the uptick due to population increases, more global travel, and changing migratory and environmental patterns that result in encroachment upon animal and other populations. And with more people living close together, outbreaks like this one will become even more common, Salama said, calling it a 'highly different paradigm.'"

"No longer will the standard be isolated rural communities that are the focus of these outbreaks, but actually dense areas of the world with high populations," he said.

In order to be prepared for ever increasing outbreaks, public-health infrastructure must be strong and maintained to be able to respond quickly. - Mod.LK]

- 6 Sep 2018. Ebola: 2 new confirmed Ebola cases in Butembo
Journal de Kinshasa [machine trans., edited]
https://www.journaldekinshasa.com/ebola-deux-nouveaux-cas-ebola-confirmes-a-butembo/

Two people died of Ebola haemorrhagic fever in the town of Butembo, opening another outbreak of infection in eastern DRC. A total of 195 people were identified as having been in contact with these 2 patients and must now urgently be vaccinated, but in the area, the fight against the epidemic is complicated because of the numerous population displacements and security problems. The 1st Ebola victim in Butembo town was known to the Congolese health services. This is a woman identified as carrying the disease in Beni, but who refused to be vaccinated and went to Butembo, thus opening another focus of contamination. As proof, the nurse who treated her is the 2nd confirmed Ebola case in Butembo; she died too. 195 people were identified by the health services as having been in contact with these 2 people. People must be vaccinated urgently according to Dr. Ndjoloklo Tambwe Bathe, sent by the Ministry to organize the response.

Another emergency for the doctor is to ensure the safety of these teams in the area. "In keeping with the international health regulations, we cannot prevent people from moving around. This is a 1st factor. The 2nd is the security issue. Our teams do not move as we want. Here, security supplants the whole response. Today, for example, my teams did not go to Butembo because safety was not guaranteed on the road."

Located 55 km [34 mi] from Beni, Butembo is an agglomeration of nearly a million inhabitants. And it has important trade links with neighboring Uganda.

[Byline: Emmanuelle Omondo]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Mary Marshall

[This is exactly what was feared would happen with expansion of Ebola to this highly urban area, and especially an area where safety is not assured. With 195 people having had contact with the infected individuals, vaccination is urgently needed. Healthcare workers should all be vaccinated before cases are introduced into their clinics and hospitals in anticipation of cases. Public health should override accepted protocols of allowing contacts to move around freely, i.e., quarantine of infected individuals would prevent the disease from spreading further if it could be enacted. - Mod.LK]

[The elopement of a known contact, and the unsafe burial from which the infection apparently originated, are clear-cut examples of community resistance in Beni (as we covered in Ebola Update (82)). The exportation of the disease to Butembo with the reported death of an HCW is a clear-cut consequence of such behavior, resulting in expansion of disease foci with fatal consequences to others. The situation is very analogous to the quarantine breaches early in the Equateur outbreak that we discussed in Ebola Update (15).

If the nurse in the Butembo university clinic did indeed die of EVD contracted from the escapee patient from Beni, this raises the question of whether that nurse had been vaccinated against Ebola or not. If so, this would apparently represent the 1st case of vaccine failure, at least in an HCW. If not, this then raises the question of whether all HCWs in North Kivu and surrounding areas should be vaccinated, if they have not already been, against such an eventuality.

In addition, this case of an absconded contact reveals the limitations of travel checkpoints on routes leading out from an outbreak area. The article above states that the "escapee" contact had refused vaccination, and even if she had been stopped at a thermometer checkpoint between Beni and Butembo, she may well have been asymptomatic. Such individuals, if they are determined to "go underground" and are sheltered by knowing or unknowing family and friends, can be very difficult indeed to trace. Let us hope that this tragic outcome can at least be used as an object lesson to overcome community resistance to Ebola control efforts. - Mod.LXL

